## 14. Data Architecture Principles

1. **Single canonical identifier per question** — `id` and `standardId` are stable foreign keys forever.
2. **Section ID normalization** — Internal section keys are distinct from display labels; aliases map legacy names.
3. **Content versioning** — Every content file carries semver or structured version; snapshots record which version was used.
4. **Scoring versioning** — Threshold and methodology changes bump scoring version; never silently retroactive.
5. **Separation of content and rules** — Questions/explanations/improvements are content; thresholds/weights are configuration.
6. **Snapshot immutability** — Completed assessments stored as point-in-time records.
7. **Minimal persistence** — Store only what serves the user; default local-only.
8. **Schema evolution** — Migrations must handle old `localStorage` keys gracefully.
9. **Authoring pipeline** — One authoritative content path; draft files (e.g., `[final_questions.txt`) are not runtime sources.
10. **RTL-safe storage** — JSON UTF-8; no encoding assumptions that corrupt Urdu/Arabic text.

### Conceptual Data Relationships

```
questionnaire (master)
  ├── responseScale
  └── questions[]
        ├── id, standardId  (immutable keys)
        ├── sectionId       (registry reference)
        ├── question, explanation, improvement
        └── options[]

sections registry
  └── sectionId, displayName, sortOrder, aliases[]

scoring config
  └── thresholds, reverseScoringRules, performanceLevels

assessment snapshot
  └── answers, report, contentVersion, scoringVersion, completedAt
```

